PRD: Add Optimistic Locking (lock_version) to All Financial Tables

1. Overview

No table in the entire schema has a `lock_version` column. This means ActiveRecord's optimistic locking is completely unavailable. While the concurrency locking PRD addresses pessimistic (`FOR UPDATE`) locking for high-contention operations, optimistic locking is needed for lower-contention scenarios: background jobs, admin updates, report generation, and long-running operations that cannot hold a row lock for their duration. Without `lock_version`, concurrent updates to the same record silently overwrite each other — the last write wins with no error, no retry, and no audit trail.

2. Goals

Add `lock_version` column to all financial tables and high-contention tables

Enable `ActiveRecord::Base#optimistic_locking` for automatic stale-object detection

Prevent silent lost-update scenarios on all table writes

Provide consistent behavior: concurrent writes raise `ActiveRecord::StaleObjectError` instead of silently overwriting

3. Non-Goals

Add `lock_version` to purely reference/read-only tables (e.g., `cooperatives`, `management_branches`, `management_roles`)

Replace pessimistic (`FOR UPDATE`) locking — optimistic and pessimistic locking serve different use cases

Remove manual locking from high-contention paths (they stay pessimistic)

Change existing validation or save patterns

4. Current State Audit

Tables without `lock_version` (all):

| Table | Contention Risk | Scenario |
|-------|----------------|----------|
| `accounting_entries` | Medium | Concurrent reversal attempts race |
| `accounting_amount_lines` | Medium | Concurrent entry posting to same entry |
| `accounting_running_balances` | High | Concurrent balance updates for same account/date |
| `loans` | High | Concurrent disbursement/restructure |
| `loan_payments` | High | Concurrent payment recording |
| `loan_schedules` | Low | Background payment posting |
| `loan_events` | Low | Event recording (mostly append-only) |
| `treasury_savings_accounts` | High | Concurrent deposit/withdraw |
| `treasury_savings_transactions` | Medium | Transaction recording |
| `treasury_cash_sessions` | High | Concurrent teller operations |
| `equity_accounts` | Medium | Share purchases |
| `equity_transactions` | Medium | Transaction recording |
| `members` | Low | Profile updates |
| `users` | Low | Password changes, profile updates |
| `management_approval_requests` | Medium | Concurrent approval/rejection |
| `management_configurations` | Low | Admin updates |

Without `lock_version`, every update to these tables is susceptible to lost updates.

5. Requirements

5.1 Must-Have

- `lock_version` column (`integer`, default `0`, null: false) on all financial tables
- ActiveRecord optimistic locking enabled for all affected models
- Background jobs that update financial records handle `ActiveRecord::StaleObjectError` with reload + retry
- All call sites that perform `UPDATE` on financial records are reviewed for optimistic locking compatibility

5.2 Nice-to-Have

- `lock_version` added to all tables (not just financial) for consistency
- Circuit breaker on retry for background jobs (max 3 retries then dead letter queue)
- `lock_version` exposed in admin audit views for debugging

6. Proposed Design

6.1 Migration

```ruby
class AddLockVersionToFinancialTables < ActiveRecord::Migration[8.0]
  def change
    add_column :accounting_entries, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
    add_column :accounting_amount_lines, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
    add_column :accounting_running_balances, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
    add_column :loans, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
    add_column :loan_payments, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
    add_column :loan_schedules, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
    add_column :loan_events, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
    add_column :treasury_savings_accounts, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
    add_column :treasury_savings_transactions, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
    add_column :treasury_cash_sessions, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
    add_column :equity_accounts, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
    add_column :equity_transactions, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
    add_column :members, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
    add_column :management_approval_requests, :lock_version, :integer, default: 0, null: false
  end
end
```

6.2 Background Job Retry Pattern

```ruby
class ApplicationJob < ActiveJob::Base
  # Override retry_on for stale object errors
  retry_on ActiveRecord::StaleObjectError, wait: :exponentially_longer, attempts: 3 do |job, error|
    job.retry_job if job.attempts < 3
    # After 3 attempts, file to dead letter queue
    Rails.logger.error("Job #{job.class} failed after 3 retries due to stale object: #{error.message}")
  end
end
```

6.3 Pessimistic + Optimistic Locking Coexistence

- `Model.lock("FOR UPDATE").find(id)` uses pessimistic locking and does NOT increment `lock_version`
- `model.save` (without `FOR UPDATE`) increments `lock_version` and raises `StaleObjectError` on conflict
- Services using `FOR UPDATE` do not need the model to have a matching `lock_version` — both can coexist
- `model.update!(...)` without `FOR UPDATE` will raise `StaleObjectError` if the record was modified since load

7. Migration Plan

- Run migration to add `lock_version` columns (zero-downtime — adding nullable column with default is fast)
- Backfill `lock_version = 0` for all existing rows (default handles new rows; existing rows get 0 on first write — PostgreSQL default applies to new rows, existing rows need explicit update if they have NULL)
- After migration, run: `UPDATE accounting_entries SET lock_version = 0 WHERE lock_version IS NULL` for each table
- Update background jobs to handle `StaleObjectError`
- No data migration needed beyond the backfill
- Rollback: remove `lock_version` columns (no data loss)

8. Risks & Mitigations

Risk: Existing code that uses `save` without `lock_version` awareness will start raising `StaleObjectError`
Mitigation: All code paths that update financial records must be reviewed. The migration itself doesn't change behavior — `lock_version` only takes effect when ActiveRecord loads a record with a value and tries to save it. Existing records loaded before the migration (without `lock_version` in the `SELECT`) will not have optimistic locking until they are reloaded after a deploy.

Risk: Batch updates (`update_all`) bypass optimistic locking
Mitigation: `update_all` does not increment `lock_version`. This is acceptable for bulk operations (e.g., nightly batch jobs) but those operations must be idempotent and not race with user-facing writes.

Risk: Background jobs get stuck on `StaleObjectError` retry loops
Mitigation: Max 3 retries with exponential backoff. After 3 failures, the job logs an error and stops. A monitoring alert fires on the error log.

9. Definition of Done

- `lock_version` column added to all 14 financial tables
- Default value `0`, not null constraint
- Backfill query run for existing rows
- `ApplicationJob` includes `retry_on ActiveRecord::StaleObjectError` with exponential backoff
- All financial models inherit `lock_version` behavior automatically (ActiveRecord default)
- RSpec tests verify: concurrent save to same record raises `StaleObjectError`; background job retries on stale error
- All existing tests pass with no new failures

10. Codebase Implementation Details

10.1 File Manifest

- `db/migrate/*_add_lock_version_to_financial_tables.rb` — new migration
- `app/jobs/application_job.rb` — add `retry_on ActiveRecord::StaleObjectError`
- No model changes needed — ActiveRecord automatically uses `lock_version` when the column exists

10.2 Existing Patterns to Follow

- Migration: Follow `db/migrate/20260621000011_consolidate_tables.rb` pattern — reversible, `add_column` with defaults
- Job retry: Follow `app/jobs/application_job.rb:6-9` pattern — `retry_on ActiveRecord::Deadlocked` (currently commented out)
- Model conventions: All financial models already use `ActiveRecord::Base` — `lock_version` is automatic, no code changes needed

